\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spatial scale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:interpolationSpatial"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
MPAs exist in a spatial context. The characteristic spatial scale of productivity, diversity and habitat found in the MPA will determine which processes will be relevant to these aspects of an MPA. If the spatial variations in the productivity of a species of interest is small relative to the size of an MPA, the chances of the MPA having an influence upon the species is enhanced. This is usually the case when short-range processes dominate (e.g., less mobile species, weakly dispersing, low currents, habitat heterogeneity at small scales). If, however, the spatial scale is larger than the MPA, then it would mean that broader/larger processes were influencing the productivity of the species (e.g., higher mobility or dispersal processes/current, and stronger spatial connectivity, habitat heterogeneity at larger scales) – resulting in a lower likelihood of the MPA having an influence upon the species or components of interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
A second important factor is the relationship of the characteristic spatial scale to monitoring. As organisms exist at a given spatial scale in a given area, a sampling/monitoring protocol must reference/address these spatial scales. For example, when a spatial feature (e.g., biodiversity) demonstrates short characteristic spatial scales (i.e., a lot of spatial structure at smaller scales), any sampling approach must respect this and similarly operate at such shorter scales or even smaller if one is to be able to resolve the patterns and describe properly the subject of interest. Similarly, if a feature (e.g., biodiversity) is long-ranged and one wishes to resolve the patterns properly, then a sampling protocol must be similarly long-ranged to resolve the pattern. A sampling program much smaller than the characteristic spatial scale would be beneficial, but the accrued benefits relative to cost of sampling would be rapidly diminishing, in that time, effort and resources requirements generally increase more rapidly than any benefit (e.g., in the simplest case, if one is looking only naively at standard error as a measure of benefit, then it would increase asymptotically with increased effort with a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
For these fundamental reasons, defining the spatial scale of a given observation or process is imperative for the development of any assessment or monitoring of MPAs. To this end, we represent any spatially explicit observation as 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

, which are measured in a coordinate space 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ \bm{s} \in S \in \Re^d \}$
\end_inset

 and domain 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of dimensionality 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

. In this framework, we will mainly focus upon the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset

 spatial dimensions (e.g., longitude and latitude or northing and easting). The observations 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

 are assumed to be realizations of a 
\series bold
spatial stochastic process
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, that is, some latent, unobservable but real stochastic generative function. The manner in which the variability of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 changes as a function of distance 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\| \bm{s} - \bm{s}' \|$
\end_inset

, is known as the spatial autocorrelation function or in a slightly different form as a (semi-) variogram. This spatial dependence is highly informative in that it defines how similarity changes with distance and so ultimately defines 
\series bold
spatial scale
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
The spatial model is succinctly expressed as a regression model of a stochastic process (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "banerjee2014hierarchical"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Y(\bm{s}) = \mu(\bm{s}) + e(\bm{s})
\label{eq:spatialModel}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
where, the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

 are a function of some mean process 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

, and a residual error process 
\begin_inset Formula $e(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

. The latter are further defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large

\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
  \mu(\bm{s}) &=& x(\bm{s})^{T} \beta \\
  e(\bm{s})  &=& \omega(\bm{s}) + \varepsilon(\bm{s})
\end{eqnarray*}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

 are spatially referenced predictors with associated parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

; and the residual error process is decomposed into spatial 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

 and nonspatial 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\bm{s})$
\end_inset

 components. The latter is also known as "nugget" error in geostatistics and represents error associated with measurement and/or microscale variability/processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
The error structures are usually assumed to be the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large

\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
  \varepsilon(\bm{s})  &\sim& \textrm{N}(0, \tau^2) \\
  \omega(\bm{s}) &\sim& \textrm{GP}(0, C(\bm{s},\bm{s}'; \bm{\theta}))  \\
  \bm{Y} &\sim& \textrm{MVN}( \bm{\mu}, \bm{\Sigma}). 
\end{eqnarray*}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
The nonspatial error is assumed normal with mean 0 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

. The spatial error is assumed to follow a Gaussian Process with mean 0 and covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\bm{s},\bm{s}'; \bm{\theta})$
\end_inset

, that is, a 
\shape italic
spatial covariance function
\shape default
 with parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\theta}$
\end_inset

. A multivariate normal likelihood is usually assumed for the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{Y} = (Y(\bm{s}_1), \dots, Y(\bm{s}_n) )^T$
\end_inset

, with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\mu} = \bm{X} \bm{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Sigma} = \left[ C(\bm{s}_i, \bm{s}_j; \theta) \right]^{n}_{i,j=1}+ \tau^2 I_n$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{X} = \left[ \bm{x}(\bm{s}_i)^T \right]^{n}_{i=1}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix of regressors and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_n$
\end_inset

 is an identity matrix of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
The spatial covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C(h) = C(\bm{s}, \bm{s}')$
\end_inset

 expresses the tendency of observations closer together to be more similar to each other than those further away; 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\| \bm{s} - \bm{s}' \|$
\end_inset

 is the distance separating observations. Historically, a number of different forms have been used. The most frequently used forms include (for 
\begin_inset Formula $h>0$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large

\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
  C(h)_{\textrm{Spherical}} &=& 
    \begin{cases}    
      \sigma^2( 1 - \frac{3}{2} h/\phi + \frac{1}{2}(h/\phi)^3 )  ; &   0 < h <= \phi \\
      0  ; &  h > \phi 
    \end{cases}  \\
  C(h)_{\text{Exponential}} &=& \sigma^2 ( \exp(-h/\phi) )   \\
  C(h)_{\text{Gaussian}} &=& \sigma^2 ( \exp(-(h/\phi)^2) ) \\
  C(h)_{\text{Powered exponential}} &=& \sigma^2 ( \exp(-| h/\phi | ^p) ) \\
  C(h)_{\text{Mat\'{e}rn}} &=& \sigma^2 \frac{1}{2^{\nu-1}\Gamma(\nu) } ( \sqrt{2\nu} h/\phi )^\nu \ K_{\nu} ( \sqrt{2\nu} h/\phi  )  .
\end{eqnarray*}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
At zero distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $C(0) = Cov( Y(s), Y(s)) = Var(Y(s)) = \tau^2 + \sigma^2$
\end_inset

 (
\shape italic
i.e.
\shape default
, global variance), where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the nonspatial error, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the spatial error, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\{\phi, \nu, p, \dots \}$
\end_inset

 are function-specific parameters including 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 the 
\shape italic
range
\shape default
 parameter. 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\cdotp)$
\end_inset

 is the Gamma function and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\nu}(\cdotp)$
\end_inset

 is the Bessel function of the second kind with smoothness 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

. The latter, Matérn covariance function is particularly appealing and more frequently used as the shape of this function is more flexible (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:matern_acf"

\end_inset

), albeit at the cost of an additional parameter (Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:matern"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

