}
\end_layout

\end_inset

. It is our opinion that this phenomenological interpretation renders it so useful as a general characterisation of system state. The argument is that the rate of change in time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 of any state 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 (in our context: abundance, species richness, "habitat", size) can be expected to be in some way, a function of itself:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
par 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray} 
\label{eqLogisticContinuous}
dY / dt = g(Y).
\end{eqnarray}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
par 
\end_layout

\end_inset

It is expected that when 
\begin_inset Formula $Y = 0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dY/dt$
\end_inset

 will also be zero and so represents an algebraic root of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

. A Taylor series expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 near this root 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=0$
\end_inset

 gives:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
par 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*} 
  \label{eqLogisticTaylorSeries}
  dY / dt &=&  g'(0) Y + g''(0) Y^{2}/2  + \text{higher order terms} \dots; \\
  &\approx& Y [g'(0) + g''(0) Y/2  ].
\end{eqnarray*}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
par 
\end_layout

\end_inset

With the identities 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(0) = r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g''(0) = - 2r/K$
\end_inset

, the standard form of the logistic equation is obtained:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
par 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} 
\label{eqLogistic}
dY/dt \approx r Y (1 - Y/K).
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
par 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The intrinsic rate of increase, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, is therefore, some abstract and aggregate function that describes the net increase or decrease of the system state 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is small. In biological systems, this means a maximum rate of growth, recruitment, mortality, movement, climatic change, extinction, speciation, etc. as the rate is expected to decline as it approaches some upper limit 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of the magnitude of the system state 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
